"response_text": "The mean factor influencing the choice of the incumbent product initiates at 1.0000 and exhibits a consistent upward trajectory, concluding at 1.0502 over the 33 recorded periods. Statistical analysis reveals a highly stable progression with minimal deviation, evidenced by a low variance of 0.0001 and a standard deviation of 0.0110. Rolling Mann-Kendall tests confirm a statistically significant increasing trend (p=0.027) across all evaluated windows. Notable inflection indices occur at steps 7 and 12, suggesting minor shifts in the rate of change, yet the overall direction remains persistently positive. For decision-makers, this stability in the incumbent habit factor implies that consumer inertia acts as a persistent brake on market transition. The persistence of this factor suggests that any significant shift away from the traditional product requires active intervention to overcome a deeply ingrained behavioral baseline that naturally resists decay."
}

